mantisshrimp69 2025-12-15 12:33 p.m.
This is about "sign[ing] off on certain rulings" not reviewing rulings. What Brenda here is referring to is 5 M.S.C. 1  2203.12203.1(a) ("A judge may, by order, designate a magistrate to hear and determine any pretrial matter pending before the court, save for the following matters [absent approval from the supervising district judge . . . ."). Here, a magistrate judge cannot take certain actions without first running them by their supervising judge. That is truethe supervising judge in this scenario, who appointed the magistrate judge for pretrial matters, is the only one that can allow them to take this action.
However, in our case,  2203.2, when a judge reviews an already-made decision that he considers contrary to law, any willing district judge can actually make that determination. See State v. Devstrious.
